            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>The Scenario: 8% CTR but 0.3% CVR—Can This Creative Actually Work?</h2>
<p>Last Wednesday, Xiao Lin, an optimizer for a utility App, discovered a puzzling ad during creative review: CTR reached 8%, well above the industry average of 2%, with a CPC of just $0.15. The metrics looked excellent. But when he opened the conversion data, his heart sank—CPA was $12 while the product price converted to only $9.99, meaning the team lost $2 on every user acquired.</p>
<p>Xiao Lin's first reaction: "The creative runs well, but can't sell."</p>
<p>This is a problem every international advertiser encounters—the gap between surface-level creative metrics and final ROI.</p>
<hr />
<h2>What "Runs" vs. What "Sells" Actually Mean</h2>
<p>In Meta's advertising ecosystem, creative performance can be measured on two dimensions:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Dimension</th>
<th>Runs (High CTR)</th>
<th>Sells (High ROI)</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Core Metrics</td>
<td>High CTR, engagement rate</td>
<td>High conversions, CVR, ROAS</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>User Psychology</td>
<td>Attracted to click</td>
<td>Convinced to pay</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Common Issues</td>
<td>Drop-off after click, abandonment</td>
<td>Difficulty scaling, cost fluctuation</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The two aren't contradictory, but they're not the same either. A "running" creative makes users stop and click; a "selling" creative makes them complete registration, subscribe, or purchase.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Four Steps to Identify Your Creative Type</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Verify Complete Funnel Data</h3>
<p>Don't jump to conclusions when reviewing a creative. First confirm whether you have complete funnel data:</p>
<ul>
<li>Impressions → Clicks (CTR)</li>
<li>Clicks → Landing page views (Page arrival rate)</li>
<li>Landing page → Add-to-cart/Registration (Conversion event)</li>
<li>Registration → Purchase (Paid rate)</li>
</ul>
<p>If the data chain is broken—if you only see CTR and CPA without the intermediate steps—you can't pinpoint where the problem lies.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Calculate Click-to-Purchase Drop-off Rate</h3>
<p>Back to Xiao Lin's case:</p>
<ul>
<li>Creative CTR: 8%, CPC: $0.15</li>
<li>Landing page CVR: 0.3%</li>
<li>CPA: $12</li>
<li>Product price: $9.99</li>
</ul>
<p>Calculate the click-to-conversion drop-off: 1000 impressions generate 80 clicks, of which only 2.4 convert (80 × 3%). This 3% isn't just "low landing page CVR"—it's the total decay from click to purchase.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Benchmark Against Historical Performance</h3>
<p>Compare current creative funnel data against similar creatives running simultaneously.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If CTR is high but CVR is low, the creative is creating "wrong expectations"—users expect Feature A from the ad, but the landing page shows Feature B, causing drop-off from expectation mismatch.</p>
<p>If both CTR and CVR are low but impressions and spend are high, the creative is "riding trends" without establishing brand/product relevance.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>Step 4: Distinguish "Fake" vs. "Real" Conversions</h3>
<p>Sometimes you see decent conversion numbers, but closer inspection reveals:</p>
<ul>
<li>Most converting users are first-order discount users with extremely low repeat purchase rates</li>
<li>Many "add-to-cart" actions but few "checkouts"</li>
<li>New user registrations with zero product usage within 7 days</li>
</ul>
<p>These "fake conversions" temporarily lower CPA but increase long-term acquisition costs. The benchmark: <strong>Does the user show repeat behavior within 30 days?</strong></p>
<hr />
<h2>Action Items: Optimization Strategies by Creative Type</h2>
<h3>For "Runs but Doesn't Sell" Creatives</h3>
<p><strong>Problem Diagnosis</strong>: Users were "tricked" into the landing page with mismatched expectations.</p>
<p><strong>Action Plan</strong>:</p>
<ol>
<li>Pause this creative from primary campaign spending</li>
<li>Demote the creative to a test group to observe click-user demographics and geography</li>
<li>Revise creative copy—add specific feature descriptions instead of pure emotional appeal</li>
<li>Simultaneously optimize landing page above-the-fold to match the creative's core promise</li>
<li>Re-run A/B tests to validate "precise creative + matching landing page" combinations</li>
</ol>
<p>After Xiao Lin implemented this process, the new creative's CTR dropped to 5%, but CPA fell to $4.2 and ROAS improved from 0.8 to 2.3.</p>
<h3>For "Sells but Doesn't Run" Creatives</h3>
<p><strong>Problem Diagnosis</strong>: The creative is too niche, only attracting high-intent users within a too-small audience pool.</p>
<p><strong>Action Plan</strong>:</p>
<ol>
<li>Expand audience targeting—test interest word combinations or lookalike audiences</li>
<li>Add "universal pain points" in the first 3 seconds to first attract attention broadly, then convert precisely</li>
<li>Lower bids or switch to CPI billing to let the creative continue learning within limited budgets</li>
<li>Test different placements, especially Reels and Stories environments with lower interference</li>
</ol>
<h3>For Creatives That "Neither Run Nor Sell"</h3>
<p><strong>Problem Diagnosis</strong>: This is likely a product-market fit issue, not a creative quality problem.</p>
<p><strong>Action Plan</strong>:</p>
<ol>
<li>Return to user research—reconfirm core needs of target users</li>
<li>Run product tests—same product with different category creatives, or same audience with different products</li>
<li>Check historical account data for reusable creative frameworks from similar products</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2>Review Isn't About Metrics—It's About Reconstructing User Decision Paths</h2>
<p>The core of creative review isn't "which numbers look good"—it's reconstructing every decision node from ad view to payment completion.</p>
<p>Separating "runs" from "sells" enables more precise optimization actions: if it runs but doesn't sell, the problem is in the first 3 seconds of expectation design; if it sells but doesn't run, the problem is audience targeting precision. If neither works, the issue is product-market fit itself.</p>
<p>Next time you review, ask yourself: What kind of person does this creative attract? Did that person ultimately pay? If not, where exactly did the money get stuck?</p>
